A few R&D folks and editors down at WotC got into an extended discussion last 
week about what it actually means when a card uses the "as though" phrasing 
(i.e. "Walls can attack as though they were not Walls") -- for example, if 
there were a hypothetical card in play that said "Whenever a Wall attacks, 
destroy it at end of turn" should it trigger?

Midway through this discussion it suddenly dawned on me that this was 
parallelling the "legal deeming" discussions held on Agora some time ago.  I 
had a vague recollection of someone writing a long post, essay, or 
dissertation that summarized much of this.  If such a thing does exist, can 
anyone point me to it?

  - Agoraphobe BethMo


